e can envy him.\x{201d}\x{2014}\x{201c}You\x{2019}re probably right.\x{201d} Our table was placed right against a partition; behind it was a private booth, from which laughter and bursts of indistinct voices were emanating. I drank a little wine. \x{201c}Still,\x{201d} I added, \x{201c}I have to admit that I had trouble understanding him.\x{201d}\x{2014}\x{201c}Not me,\x{201d} Hohenegg asserted. \x{201c}You see, in my view there are three possible attitudes faced with this absurd life. First the attitude of the mass, hoi polloi, which simply refuses to see that life is a joke. They don\x{2019}t laugh at it, but work, accumulate, masticate, defecate, fornicate, reproduce, get old, and die like oxen harnessed to the plow, as idiotic as they lived. That\x{2019}s the large majority. Then there are those, such as me, who know that life is a joke and who have the courage to laugh at it, like the Taoists or your Jew. Finally there are those, and if my diagnosis is correct you are one of them, who know that life is a joke, but who suffer from it. It\x{2019}s like your Lermontov, whom I\x{2019}ve finally read: I zhizn takaya pustaya i glupaya shutka, he writes.\x{201d} I knew enough Russian now to understand and complete the phrase: \x{201c}He should have added: i grubaya, \x{2018}an empty, stupid and dirty joke.\x{2019}\x{201d}\x{2014}\x{201c}He certainly thought of it. But it wouldn\x{2019}t have scanned right.\x{201d}\x{2014}\x{201c}Those who have that attitude do know, however, that the other laughing one exists,\x{201d} I said.\x{2014}\x{201c}Yes, but they don\x{2019}t manage to adopt it.\x{201d} The voices on the other side of the partition had become clearer: a waitress had left the curtain of the booth open as she went out. I recognized the coarse intonations of Turek and his lackey Pfeiffer. \x{201c}Women like that should be banned from the SS!\x{201d} Turek was screeching.\x{2014}\x{201c}That\x{2019}s right. He should be in a concentration camp, not a uniform,\x{201d} Pfeiffer replied.\x{2014}\x{201c}Yes,\x{201d} said another voice, \x{201c}but you need evidence.\x{201d}\x{2014}\x{201c}We saw them,\x{201d} said Turek. \x{201c}The other day, behind the Mashuk. They left the road to go do their things in the woods.\x{201d}\x{2014}\x{201c}Are you sure?\x{201d}\x{2014}\x{201c}I give you my word as an officer.\x{201d}\x{2014}\x{201c}And you recognized him?\x{201d}\x{2014}\x{201c}Aue? He was as close to me as you are now.\x{201d} The men suddenly fell silent. Turek turned slowly around and saw me standing in the entrance to the booth. His flushed face drained of blood. Pfeiffer, at the head of the table, went yellow. \x{201c}It is very regrettable that you should use your word as an officer so lightly, Hauptsturmf\x{fc}hrer,\x{201d} I said clearly, in a measured, neutral tone. \x{201c}That devalues it. Yet there is still time to withdraw your despicable words. I warn you: if you don\x{2019}t, we must fight.\x{201d} Turek had gotten up, abruptly pushing back his chair. An absurd tic was deforming his lips, giving him an even more spineless and lost look than usual. His eyes sought out Pfeiffer, who encouraged him with a sign of his head. \x{201c}I have nothing to withdraw,\x{201d} he squeaked in a monotone. He still hesitated to go all the way. I was filled with a strong exaltation; but my voice remained calm, precise. \x{201c}Are you quite sure?\x{201d} I wanted to push him, to inflame him and slam all the doors shut behind him. \x{201c}I won\x{2019}t be as easy to kill as an unarmed Jew, you can be sure of that.\x{201d} These words provoked a commotion. \x{201c}You\x{2019}re insulting the SS!\x{201d} Pfeiffer roared. Turek was pale; he looked at me like a mad bull, without saying anything. \x{201c}Very well, then,\x{201d} I said. \x{201c}I will send someone soon to the Teilkommando offices.\x{201d} I turned on my heel and left the restaurant. Hohenegg caught up with me on the steps: \x{201c}That\x{2019}s not very smart, what you d