            "[ap 07:00] The Kindly Ones - Jonathan Littell.epub (Littell_Jonathan_split_013.html) - seven o\x{2019}clock",
            "Since then, many things had changed. The F\x{fc}hrer still had all the confidence of the Volk, but the certainty of final victory was beginning to ebb away among the masses. The people blamed the High Command, the Prussian aristocrats, G\x{f6}ring and his Luftwaffe; but I knew too that within the Wehrmacht some were blaming the interference of the F\x{fc}hrer. Within the SS, it was being whispered that he had had a nervous breakdown after Stalingrad, that he wasn\x{2019}t talking to anyone anymore; that at the beginning of the month, when Rommel had tried to convince him to evacuate North Africa, he had listened to him without comprehension. As for the public rumors, in the trains, the tramways, the lines, they were becoming downright ludicrous: according to the SD reports that Thomas received, people were saying that the Wehrmacht had put the F\x{fc}hrer under house arrest in Berchtesgaden, that he had lost his reason and was kept under guard, drugged, in an SS hospital, that the F\x{fc}hrer we saw was just a double. The speech was going to be given in the Zeughaus, the former arsenal at the end of Unter den Linden, right next to the Spree Canal. As a Stalingrad veteran, wounded and decorated, I didn\x{2019}t have any trouble getting an invitation; I suggested to Thomas that he come with me, but he replied, laughing: \x{201c}I\x{2019}m not on leave, I have work to do.\x{201d} So I went alone. They had taken considerable security precautions; the invitation said that service weapons would be forbidden. The possibility of a British raid frightened some: in January, the English had reveled at launching a Mosquito attack on the anniversary of the Seizure of Power, producing many victims; yet now the chairs had been set up in the Zeughaus courtyard, under the large glass cupola. I found myself seated in the center, between an Oberstleutnant covered with decorations and a civilian wearing the Gold Badge of the Party on his lapel. After the introductory speeches, the F\x{fc}hrer made his appearance. I opened my eyes wide: on his head and shoulders, over his simple feldgrau uniform, I seemed to see a large blue-and-white striped rabbi\x{2019}s shawl. The F\x{fc}hrer had started speaking right away in his rapid, monotone voice. I examined the glass roof: Could it be a play of the light? I could clearly see his cap; but underneath it, I thought I made out long side curls, unrolling along his temples down over his lapel, and on his forehead, the tefillin, the little leather box containing verses of the Torah. When he raised his arm, I thought I could make out other leather straps bound around his wrist; and under his jacket, weren\x{2019}t those the white fringes of what the Jews call the little tallith showing through? I didn\x{2019}t know what to think. I scrutinized my neighbors: they were listening to the speech with solemn attention, the civil servant was studiously nodding his head. Didn\x{2019}t they notice anything? Was I the only one to see this unprecedented spectacle? I looked at the dignitaries\x{2019} stand: behind the F\x{fc}hrer, I recognized G\x{f6}ring, Goebbels, Ley, the Reichsf\x{fc}hrer, Kaltenbrunner, other well-known leaders, high-ranking Wehrmacht officers; they were all contemplating the F\x{fc}hrer\x{2019}s back or the audience, impassive. Maybe, I said to myself, panic-stricken, it\x{2019}s the story of the Emperor\x{2019}s New Clothes: everyone sees how it really is, but hides it, counting on his neighbor to do the same. No, I reasoned, I must be hallucinating, with a wound like mine, that\x{2019}s entirely possible. Yet I felt perfectly sound of mind. I was far from the platform, though, and the F\x{fc}hrer was lit from the side; maybe it was simply an optical illusion? But I still saw it. Maybe my \x{201c}pineal eye\x{201d} was playing a trick on me? But there was nothing dreamlike about it. It was also possible that I had gone mad. The speech was short, and I found myself standing in the midst of the crowd trying to head for the exit, unable to make any headway in my thoughts. The F\x{fc}hrer would now go to the galleries in the Zeughaus to visit an exhibition of war trophies captured from the Bolsheviks, before going on to inspect an honor guard, and place a wreath at the Neue Wache; I could have followed him, since this was included in my invitation, but I was too rattled and disoriented; I extricated myself from the crowd as quickly as possible and headed back up the avenue toward the S-Bahn station. I crossed the avenue and went to sit in a caf\x{e9}, under the arcades of the Kaiser Gallerie, where I ordered a schnapps, drained it in one swallow, then ordered another. I had to think, but the meaning of my thinking escaped me, I was having trouble breathing, I undid my collar and drank some more. There was one way to discover the truth of the matter: in the evening, at the movies, the newsreels would show excerpts from his speech; that would set me straight. I ordered a paper with a list of showings: at <<seven o\x{2019}clock|6>>, not far away, they were showing Uncle Kr\x{fc}ger. I ordered a sandwich and then went for a walk in the Tiergarten. It was still cold, and not many people were strolling under the bare trees. Different interpretations were whirling around in my head, I was impatient for the film to start, even if the prospect of seeing nothing there wasn\x{2019}t any more reassuring than the opposite. At <<six o\x{2019}clock|6>>, I headed for the movie theater and took my place in the line to buy my ticket. In front of me, a group of people were discussing the speech, which they must have heard on the radio; I listened to them eagerly. \x{201c}He blamed the Jews for everything again,\x{201d} said a skinny man wearing a hat. \x{201c}What I don\x{2019}t understand is that there aren\x{2019}t any more Jews in Germany, so how can it be their fault?\x{201d}\x{2014}\x{201c}But no, Dummkopf,\x{201d} replied a rather vulgar woman with bleached hair s