he Gruppenf\x{fc}hrers given on the fourth. If these speeches have entered history, it\x{2019}s not of course because of all that, but because in this speech the Reichsf\x{fc}hrer, with a frankness he has never to my knowledge equaled either before or since, with frankness thus and in a manner that could even be called crude, outlined the program of the destruction of the Jews. Even I, when I heard it on October 6, didn\x{2019}t at first believe my ears, the hall was full, the sumptuous Golden Hall in the castle at Posen, I was in the very back, behind about fifty Gauleiters and leaders of the Party, not to mention a few industrialists, two service chiefs, and three (or maybe two) ministers of the Reich; and I found it, considering the secrecy rules we were bound to, truly shocking, almost indecent, and at the beginning, it made me very ill at ease, and I was certainly not the only one, I could see Gauleiters sigh and mop their foreheads or necks, it wasn\x{2019}t that they were learning something new, no, everyone, in that great hall with its subdued lighting must have been in the know, even though some of them, until then, probably hadn\x{2019}t had to think the thing through to the end, to discern its full extent, to think, for instance, about the women and children, and that\x{2019}s probably why the Reichsf\x{fc}hrer insisted on this point, far more, moreover, to the Reichsleiters and Gauleiters than to his Gruppenf\x{fc}hrers, who couldn\x{2019}t in any case have had any illusions, which is probably why he insisted that, yes, we were indeed killing the women and the children too, so as not to let any ambiguity linger, and that\x{2019}s precisely what was so uncomfortable, that total absence, for once, of ambiguity, and it was as if he were violating an unwritten rule, even stronger than his own rules he decreed for his subordinates, his Sprachregelungen already absolutely strict, the rule of tact perhaps, that tact he spoke of in his first speech, evoking it in the context of the execution of R\x{f6}hm and his SA comrades, a kind of natural tact that is alive in us, thank God, he said, a consequence of this tact due to which we have never spoken about it among ourselves, but perhaps it was also a matter of something other than the question of that tact and of those rules, and that\x{2019}s when I began to understand, I think, the profound reason for these declarations, and also why the dignitaries sighed and sweated so much, for they too, like me, were beginning to understand, to understand that it wasn\x{2019}t by chance that the Reichsf\x{fc}hrer, in the beginning of the fifth year of the war, was thus openly referring to the destruction of the Jews before them, without euphemisms, without winks, with simple and brutal words like kill\x{2014}exterminate, he said, meaning kill or order to have killed\x{2014} that, for once, the Reichsf\x{fc}hrer spoke to them quite openly about this question\x{2026}to tell you how it was, no, that certainly wasn\x{2019}t by chance, and if he allowed himself to do it, then the F\x{fc}hrer knew about it, and worse, the F\x{fc}hrer had wanted it, hence their anguish, the Reichsf\x{fc}hrer was speaking necessarily here in the name of the F\x{fc}hrer, and he was saying this, these words that you weren\x{2019}t supposed to say, and he was recording them, on a disk or a tape, it doesn\x{2019}t matter, and he was carefully taking note of those present and those absent\x{2014}among the SS leaders, the only ones who didn\x{2019}t attend the October 4 speech were Kaltenbrunner, who was sick with phlebitis, Daluege, who had a serious heart disease and was on leave for a year or two, Wolff, just recently appointed HSSPF for Italy and plenipotentiary to Mussolini, and Globocnik, who had just, although I didn\x{2019}t know it yet and heard about it only after Posen, suddenly been transferred from his little Lublin kingdom to his native town of Trieste, as SSPF for Istria and Dalmatia, under Wolff\x{20