            "You must find these reflections extremely interesting, I don\x{2019}t doubt it for an instant; but I have wandered off the subject a little, I still haven\x{2019}t spoken of that famous day of October 6, which I wanted to describe briefly. A few quick knocks on the door of my compartment had tugged me from my sleep; with the blinds fastened, it was impossible to know the time, I was probably in the midst of a dream, I remember being completely disoriented by them. Then I heard the voice of Mandelbrod\x{2019}s assistant, gentle but firm: \x{201c}Sturmbannf\x{fc}hrer. We\x{2019}re arriving in half an hour.\x{201d} I washed, got dressed, and went to stretch my legs in the antechamber. The young woman was standing there: \x{201c}Hello, Sturmbannf\x{fc}hrer. Did you sleep well?\x{201d}\x{2014}\x{201c}Yes, thanks. Is Dr. Mandelbrod awake?\x{201d}\x{2014}\x{201c}I don\x{2019}t know, Sturmbannf\x{fc}hrer. Would you like some coffee? A full breakfast will be served when we arrive.\x{201d} She returned with a small tray. I drank the coffee standing up, my legs slightly apart because of the train\x{2019}s swaying; she sat down on a little armchair, her legs discreetly crossed\x{2014}she was wearing now, I noticed, a long skirt instead of the black breeches of the day before. Her hair was pulled back in a severe chignon. \x{201c}You aren\x{2019}t having any?\x{201d} I asked.\x{2014}\x{201c}No, thanks.\x{201d} We stayed thus in silence until the squeal of brakes sounded. I gave her back the cup and took my travel bag. The train was slowing down. \x{201c}Have a good day,\x{201d} she said. \x{201c}Dr. Mandelbrod will find you later on.\x{201d} On the platform, there was a certain amount of confusion; the tired Gauleiters were exiting the train one by one, yawning, welcomed by a squad of civil servants in civilian clothes or in SA uniform. One of them saw my SS uniform and frowned. I pointed to Mandelbrod\x{2019}s car, and his face lit up: \x{201c}I\x{2019}m sorry,\x{201d} he said as he came forward. I gave him my name, and he consulted a list: \x{201c}Yes, I see. You are with the members of the Reichsf\x{fc}hrung, at the Posen Hotel. There\x{2019}s a room for you. I\x{2019}ll go find you a car. Here\x{2019}s the program.\x{201d} At the hotel, a fancy but rather staid building dating back to the Prussian period, I showered, shaved, changed, and downed a few pieces of toast with jam. <<Around eight o\x{2019}clock|6>>, I went down to the lobby. People were beginning to come and go. I finally found one of Brandt\x{2019}s assistants, a Hauptsturmf\x{fc}hrer, and showed him the program I had been given. \x{201c}Listen, you can go right now. The Reichsf\x{fc}hrer won\x{2019}t come until the afternoon, but there will be some officers there.\x{201d} The car lent me by the Gau was still waiting, and I had myself driven to the Schloss Posen, admiring on the way the blue belfry and the arcaded loggia of the city hall, then the many-colored fa\x{e7}ades of the narrow houses of burghers crowded onto the Old Square, reflections of many centuries of subtly fanciful architecture, until this fugitive morning pleasure collided with the castle itself, a vast pile of blocks abutting a large empty square, crude and bristling with pointed roofs and a tall buttressed tower propped against it, massive, proud, severe, dreary, in front of which the penant-bearing Mercedes of the dignitaries were lining up one by one. The program began with a series of lectures given by experts from Speer\x{2019}s entourage, including Walter Rohland, the steel magnate, who exposed one after the other, with distressing precision, the state of war production. In the first row, listening gravely to this somber news, could be seen most of the government elite: Dr. Goebbels, Minister Rosenberg, Axmann, the Reich Youth F\x{fc}hrer, Grand Admiral D\x{f6}nitz, Feldmarschall Milch from the Luftwaffe, and a beefy man with a bull\x{2019}s neck, his thick hair combed back, whose name 